Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p><ol><li>Click Submit to run the experiment and wait for the run to complete.</li><li>When the experiment finishes running, preview the output of the Evaluate Model module to examine performance of the model.</li></ol><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p><p>The following metrics are reported for evaluating regression models. When you compare models, they are ranked by the metric you select for evaluation.</p><p><strong>Mean absolute error (MAE)</strong> measures how close the predictions are to the actual outcomes; thus, a lower score is better.</p><p><strong>Root mean squared error (RMSE)</strong> creates a single value that summarizes the error in the model. By squaring the difference, the metric disregards the difference between over-prediction and under-prediction.</p><p><strong>Relative absolute error (RAE)</strong> is the relative absolute difference between expected and actual values; relative because the mean difference is divided by the arithmetic mean.</p><p><strong>Relative squared error (RSE)</strong> similarly normalizes the total squared error of the predicted values by dividing by the total squared error of the actual values.</p><p><strong>Coefficient of determination</strong>, often referred to as R2, represents the predictive power of the model as a value between 0 and 1. Zero means the model is random (explains nothing); 1 means there is a perfect fit. However, caution should be used in interpreting R2 values, as low values can be entirely normal and high values can be suspect.</p><ol><li>Note, in the next exercise, we will try a different regression algorithm and compare algorithm performance for the Flight Delays Data.</li></ol><p>Exercise 3 has been completed</p><p><a id="_Toc4326525"></a>Exercise 4: Create a Boosted Decision Tree Regression Model and compare the Results with the Linear Regression Model</p><p>Tasks</p><ol><li>Double click the Train Model module in experiment created in the previous exercise.
